node.text:
More than the launch of unparalleled works of jewelry craft, @Bulgari's Magnifica High Jewelry collection is a celebration of rebirth. Honored through magnificent muses, music, and Milan, take a look at Bvlgari's latest high jewelry collection.
 
Models: @vittoria, @lilyaldridge @heconghc, @solangesmith and @blesnyaminher
Special Guests: @andreabocelliofficial @beatricevenezi
Project by @oma.eu
Director @tommaso.ottomano
DOP@ mrcodepa
Stylist @sagliogeraldine
Music @guazzonemarco 
Production @studio.april
#Bvlgari #BvlgariJewelry #BvlgariHighJewelry #BvlgariMagnifica #Milan

node.text: After making her #NYFW modeling debut at @ProenzaSchouler, @EllaEmhoff landed a knitwear collaboration with Batsheva Hay (@batshevadress). The 21-year-old student, model, and designer met up with Hay amid NYFW—and #GoodMorningVogue was there to capture their conversations about materials, fit, and texture, plus Ella's rise to fame in the wake of the inauguration of President Joe Biden and Emhoff’s step-mother, Kamala Harris, in January.

node.text: This month, Vogue joined forces with an army of photographers and models all around the globe—stable Zoom connections required, please!—and sent the best and brightest of the new collections via courier services everywhere from Beijing to Brazil, Lagos to Los Angeles. Our concept? Simple, glorious movement: After a year of stasis, immobility and lockdowns, we wanted to see spring fashion breaking free. These are the looks we love, shot by the photographers we adore, on the run and out for a walk, a swim, a dance. Tap the link in our bio to see more.

node.text:
Today, @KamalaHarris became the first woman of color ever sworn in as vice president of the United States.

To celebrate this moment, twelve young women discussing what it means to them to see a Black woman of Indian descent elected to the second-highest office in the land. “Every little girl sees that this is a country of possibility,” @KamalaHarris states in one address, and that sentiment is widely echoed. “She reminds me every day that I am capable and worthy of my wildest dreams,” says one participant.

Director @rombokob
Producer @aliwebb_producer
Casting Director: Rebecca Dealy
Archival Research: Manon Blackman
Editor @ann_lupo
GFX @horatiobaltz
Color @carlosfloresfilms
Mix @cstropko
Post Production @forager.tv

node.title: 12 Girls on What Kamala Harris Becoming Vice President Means to Them

node.text: Throughout the political tumult of 2020, @janayathefuture was one of the most prominent voices to become a source of healing and hope. Reflecting on this week’s events, Khan points out the lack of police presence at the Capitol, a fact that exposes, in their own words, “a clear double standard for how Black protestors have been treated over the past several years. What we know to be true is that there is a way that white rage is celebrated in this country and Black grief is criminalized.” To hear more, make sure to check out Khan’s Sunday Sermons, returning tomorrow 1/10  at 12PM PST on their account.

node.title: @janayathefuture on Moving Forward from the Capitol Riots

node.text:
If you haven’t watched an episode of Ted Lasso yet, you should clear your schedule. The series, which racked up a record-breaking 20 Emmy nominations last week, is a whip-smart look at cultural and ideological differences. As model Keeley Jones, @junotemple shattered any stereotypes about soccer WAGs (wives and girlfriends) with her endearing portrayal. 

Naturally, the season 2 premiere called for a truly epic look, and to honor her character’s outré style, Temple and stylist @erinwalshstyle looked to retro @Versace runways. 

Tap the link in our bio to go behind the scenes of how this look came together–plus, how it's an ode to Kate Moss.
Photo: @christianhogstedt

node.text:
As a young girl, Sunisa Lee (@sunisalee_) was always grabbing her mom’s phone to watch gymnasts flip, then repairing to the nearest couch or bed to try one out. Her father spotted her in those days and then, as her gymnastics improved, organized fundraisers at local Hmong restaurants to help pay for travel to national and then international meets, coaxing Lee to sing, which she loved. “My dad would pick some songs,” she remembers, “and I’d say, ‘What is this song?’ ” (Once it was Bette Midler’s version of “Wind Beneath My Wings.”) The Twin Cities area is home to the largest urban Hmong community in the U.S., and when Lee wins, she is winning for the Hmong neighbors who supported her in the gym and supported her father: While helping a friend, he fell off a ladder, suffering a spinal-cord injury that paralyzed him from the chest down a few days before Lee won a gold, a silver, and a bronze medal at the national championships in 2019. Her father FaceTimed Lee at the nationals from his hospital bed to cheer her on, but no one knew what she was going through as she attempted a bar routine that she had upgraded in difficulty. As she aced the landing, the commentators predicted Tokyo gold.

A veteran of the U.S. team that won the gold at the 2019 world championships in Stuttgart, Germany, Lee was practicing her uneven-bar magic at her gym in the suburbs of St. Paul one day and doing Zoom workouts at home the next. Time stood still—until it didn’t. “It’s crazy how fast the time has gone,” she says.

At the link in our bio, we meet with three star athletes to hear about their winding road to @tokyo2020. Photographed by @JoshOlins, styledby @maxortegag, Vogue, September 2021

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Vogue on July 19, 2021 tagging @jenniferbeverly, @nojo18, @alex_jordan_harrington, and @hypewilliams. May be an image of 2 people and people playing sports.

node.text:
“Me, personally, I am somebody who loves to be social,” says Noah Lyles (@nojo18). America’s 200-meter sprinting star has already won in New York and surged ahead late—his trademark—to win at the USATF Golden Games in California. “I love to go out and hang out—and practice—with other people. I love it! To train with others and get that excitement, that…edge!”

The first @Olympics that amazed him were the 2012 London games, when he was 15 and mostly watched gymnastics. “I just thought @gabbycvdouglas was the coolest person because, one, she was young,” Lyles says. “Two, she was Black, and three, she was the first to do something.” (She was the first Black woman to win the Olympic all-around gymnastics title.) “I just thought, Yeah—I want to go out there and be somebody who’s the first to do something. The Olympics hits everybody.”

At the link in our bio, we meet with three star athletes to hear about their winding road to @tokyo2020. Photographed by @HypeWilliams, styled by @alex_jordan_harrington, Vogue, September 2021

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Vogue on July 19, 2021 tagging @danascruggs, @kaorinikstudios, @swimone, and @tonnegood. May be an image of one or more people and pool.

node.text:
As was the case for everything else, the schedule for the 2020 @Olympics did not go as planned. At the beginning of March 2020, Simone Manuel (@swimone), who won two gold and two silver medals at the 2016 Rio Olympics and was planning on continuing her streak in Tokyo, had just finished up a swim meet in Des Moines while talking to her mom. Rumors about the virus were flying. Three days after she got back to her home in California, the pool she trained in closed up, the 2020 games still theoretically on. “And nobody had a plan,” she says. 

Thanks to her coach, Manuel managed to find a backyard pool seemingly designed for her needs: two lanes, with poolside race clocks and starting blocks. The pool’s owners donated its daily use to Manuel and her former Stanford teammate @katieledecky, but the initial rush of fortunate feelings gave way to more complicated emotions in the shut-down world. “Sometimes I felt a little guilty,” Manuel recalls. “It was hard doing it knowing that the Olympics were postponed. You go through these roller-coaster emotions—you’re thinking, Ah, it’s another year to get better, and the next you’re like, But I was ready for it right now.” She did her best to keep things in perspective, but like everyone, she missed the least extraordinary things, like a trip to the mall or to the nail salon.

At the link in our bio, we meet with three star athletes to hear about their winding road to @tokyo2020. Photographed by @DanaScruggs, styled by @tonnegood, Vogue, September 2021

node.text:
The headscarf. It’s an accessory almost as old as time—history has seen women across cultures, religions, and the globe wear some version of a headscarf—but its stance as an in-demand fashion item comes and goes. But, as of the fall 2021 collections, it would very much seem that this trend is back in full force. 

Tap the link in bio to shop our favorite headscarf choices that are inspired by designers like @Versace, @Dior and more, and let @anokyai show you the perfect way to style it.

#regram @anokyai

node.text:
“Everyone knows that I love a beautiful gown and glamour, and that’s what I wanted for the award shows but for Cannes, I wanted everybody to see a different side of my style. I wanted to go fresh and a bit edgy,” @mariabakalovaofficial says. “What I loved was the casualness and the coolness that @LouisVuitton always has. Especially the green one that gives you that futuristic Jetson look!”

Tap the link in our bio to see her full photo diary. Photo: @gregwilliamsphotography.
